Title: The Lamphron Variation
Author: Flyxion
Draft: First

FADE IN:

INT. UNIVERSITY ARCHIVE — NIGHT

Fluorescent light. Long rows of steel shelving receding into darkness.
At a table near the window, MARIAN (40s, precise, eyes that hold more
than they release) spreads architectural drawings across the surface.

A manila envelope sits open beside her. Photographs. She does not look
at them yet.

ARCHIVIST (O.S.)
We close in twenty minutes.

Marian does not respond. She traces a line on the drawing with one finger.

INT. UNIVERSITY ARCHIVE — CONTINUOUS

HENRIK (50s, a man who has learned to wait) steps from between two
shelving units. He has been there for some time.

HENRIK
You found the Reinholt drawings.

MARIAN
(without looking up)
I found what was left of them.

HENRIK
That's not nothing.

MARIAN
It depends on what you were looking for.

Henrik crosses to the table. He looks at the drawings without touching them.

HENRIK
They say the structure predates the university by two centuries.

MARIAN
They say a lot of things about it.

HENRIK
What do you say?

A long pause. Marian finally looks up.

MARIAN
I say the measurements don't match any known acoustic model. I say
the chamber was not designed for silence. I say someone built something
here and we have been very careful not to notice it.

Henrik sits.

HENRIK
So you're going to make noise about it.

MARIAN
I'm going to make the noise it was designed to make. There's a
difference.

EXT. UNIVERSITY COURTYARD — NIGHT

Rain. Marian walks quickly. Henrik follows at a measured distance.

HENRIK
If you publish this you'll have every archaeoacoustics crank in
Europe writing to you.

MARIAN
They're already writing to me.

HENRIK
The serious ones then.

MARIAN
(stopping)
Henrik. The serious ones are the cranks. That's the whole problem.

She walks on. He stops, watching her go.

INT. MARIAN'S APARTMENT — KITCHEN — NIGHT

Marian at the table. The photographs finally out of the envelope.
Stone surfaces. Concave geometries. A recurring series of markings
that could be measurement notches or could be something else.

She arranges them in a grid. Studies the pattern.

She reaches for a pen. Stops. Reaches again. Writes a single number
at the bottom of a notepad.

Then beneath it, another.

The ratio between them is not incidental.

INT. MARIAN'S APARTMENT — KITCHEN — LATER

The notepad is full. The photographs have been reorganised three times.
A cold cup of tea sits at the edge of the table.

Marian looks at what she has assembled.

MARIAN
(quietly, to herself)
It isn't a theory. It's a measurement.

She closes the notepad. Opens it again. The numbers remain.

INT. UNIVERSITY CORRIDOR — DAY

Marian walking. Fast. PROFESSOR SEDLAK (60s, the kind of weariness
that has chosen to be graceful) falls into step beside her.

SEDLAK
I heard you were in the archive last night.

MARIAN
News travels.

SEDLAK
In this building it walks very slowly and arrives slightly wrong.

MARIAN
I was looking at the Reinholt drawings.

SEDLAK
And?

MARIAN
And I need access to the chamber. The actual chamber.

Sedlak stops. Marian continues two more steps before turning.

SEDLAK
Marian. The chamber is sealed. It has been sealed since 1987.

MARIAN
I know. I need it unsealed.

SEDLAK
On what grounds?

MARIAN
On the grounds that we may have been measuring the wrong thing for
thirty years.

A long moment.

SEDLAK
I'll need something in writing.

MARIAN
I'll need the key.

EXT. UNIVERSITY — SERVICE ENTRANCE — NIGHT

Henrik is waiting. He has brought a flashlight and something in a
canvas bag that clinks when he sets it down.

MARIAN
What's in the bag?

HENRIK
Equipment. What's in yours?

MARIAN
Uncertainty.

HENRIK
Good. I brought enough certainty for both of us.

She looks at him.

HENRIK (CONT'D)
That was a joke.

MARIAN
I know. It didn't help.

They go inside.

INT. SEALED CHAMBER — BENEATH THE UNIVERSITY — NIGHT

Stone. Old stone. The kind of old that precedes record-keeping.

Marian moves along the wall, running her hand across the surface.
The concave structures from the photographs are here, but larger.
More present. They occupy the room in a way that photographs cannot
convey.

Henrik sets up a measurement device. Marian watches.

MARIAN
Don't calibrate it the usual way.

HENRIK
How then?

MARIAN
Use the notches. The ones at one-point-four metre intervals along
the north wall.

Henrik looks at the wall.

HENRIK
Those are decorative.

MARIAN
Test that assumption.

He calibrates using the notches. The device settles. He looks at the
reading.

HENRIK
That can't be right.

MARIAN
I know.

HENRIK
The resonance frequency—

MARIAN
Is not an accident. I know.

A long silence. The stone around them seems to hold the sound of the
measurement in the way that very old things hold the impressions made
on them.

HENRIK
Who built this?

MARIAN
Someone who knew what they were doing. That's all I can say with
certainty right now.

HENRIK
And the rest?

Marian looks at the walls. The notches. The concavities. The geometry
that was not designed for silence.

MARIAN
The rest is what I need to prove.

She takes out the notepad. Opens it to the page of numbers.

The ratio is still there.

FADE OUT.
